{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"5da5068d-58a5-44ea-be61-fb8850c28634","content":"The standard approach in .NET is to **wrap file system calls behind an interface** so you can inject a fake/mock in tests. Two options:\n\n**1. Use `System.IO.Abstractions` (recommended)**\n```bash\ndotnet add package System.IO.Abstractions\n```\n- Replace `File.WriteAllText(...)` → `_fileSystem.File.WriteAllText(...)`\n- Replace `Directory.Exists(...)` → `_fileSystem.Directory.Exists(...)`\n- Inject `IFileSystem` via constructor; use `MockFileSystem` in tests.\n\n**2. Roll your own interface**\n```csharp\npublic interface IFileSystem\n{\n    string ReadAllText(string path);\n    void WriteAllText(string path, string contents);\n    bool DirectoryExists(string path);\n}\n```\nImplement it with real `System.IO` calls, then mock it in tests.\n\n**Option 1** is strongly preferred — it covers the entire `System.IO` surface, has a battle-tested `MockFileSystem` with an in-memory file system, and avoids maintaining your own abstraction.\n\nWant me to refactor your project to use `System.IO.Abstractions`?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"4ca0fe57-aba4-4b07-b8e1-bae881c816f1","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about making file system operations testable in a .NET/C# project. This is a design question about testability, not a code change request. Let me give them concise advice.\n\nThe standard approach is to use the `System.IO.Abstractions` library, which provides an `IFileSystem` interface that wraps all `System.IO` static calls. This lets you inject a mock/fake file system in tests.\n\nLet me give a concise answer.","outputTokens":404,"requestId":"0846:32055B:816BC0D:9014D8D:69EACC2E"},"id":"4311b924-0943-43e8-8185-ca275d8c789c","timestamp":"2026-04-24T01:49:45.663Z","parentId":"12430c70-07d9-4c88-aecf-ee065011f7d0"}
